  Series                   = {Astronomical Society of the Pacific Conference Series},
  Volume                   = {470},

  Abstract                 = {{Dense star clusters expand until their sizes are limited by the tidal
field of their host galaxy. During this expansion phase the member stars
evolve and lose mass. We show that for clusters with short initial
relaxation time scales ({\le}100 Myr) the dynamical expansion is largely
powered by mass loss from stars in the core, but happens on a relaxation
time scale. That is, the energy release following stellar mass loss is
in balance with the amount of energy that is transported outward by
two-body relaxation.
