oscillations is also important for predicting the mode parameters in the
power spectrum. <BR /> Methods: Non-adiabatic computations, including a
time-dependent treatment of convection, are performed and provide the
lifetimes of radial and non-radial mixed modes. We then combine these
mode lifetimes and inertias with a stochastic excitation model that
gives us their heights in the power spectra. <BR /> Results: For stars
representative of CoRoT and Kepler observations, we show under which
circumstances mixed modes have heights comparable to radial ones. We
stress the importance of the radiative damping in determining the height
of mixed modes. Finally, we derive an estimate for the height ratio
between a g-type and a p-type mode. This can thus be used as a first
estimate of the detectability of mixed modes.

