  Abstract                 = {{We use 612 single stars with previously published trigonometric
parallaxes placing them within 25 pc to evaluate parallaxes released in
Gaia{\rsquo}s first data release (DR1). We find that the Gaia parallaxes
are, on average, 0.24 {\plusmn} 0.02 mas smaller than the weighted mean
trigonometric parallax values for these stars in the solar neighborhood.
We also find that the offset changes with distance out to 100 pc, in the
sense that the closer the star, the larger the offset. We find no
systematic trends in the parallax offsets with stellar V magnitude, V
- K color, or proper motion. We do find that the offset is roughly
twice as large for stars south of the ecliptic compared to those that
are north.
