  Month                    = sep,

  Abstract                 = {{We present new spectroscopic observations obtained with GMOS@Gemini-S of
a sample of 25 hii regions located in NGC 55, a late-type galaxy in the
nearby Sculptor group. We derive physical conditions and chemical
composition through the te-method for 18 hii regions, and strong-line
abundances for 22 hii regions. We provide abundances of He, O, N, Ne, S,
Ar, finding a substantially homogenous composition in the ionised gas of
the disc of NGC 55, with no trace of radial gradients. The oxygen
abundances, both derived with $\backslash$te- and strong-line methods, have similar
mean values and similarly small dispersion:
12+$\log$(O/H)=8.13$\pm$0.18\~{}dex with the former and
12+$\log$(O/H)=8.17$\pm$0.13\~{}dex with the latter. The average
metallicities and the flat gradients agree with previous studies of
smaller samples of $\backslash$hii$\backslash$ regions and there is a qualitative agreement
with the blue supergiant radial gradient as well. We investigate the
origin of such flat gradients comparing NGC 55 with NGC 300, its
companion galaxy, which is also twin of NGC 55 in terms of mass and
luminosity. We suggest that the differences in the metal distributions
in the two galaxies might be related to the differences in their K-band
surface density profile. The flatter profile of NGC 55 probably causes
in this galaxy higher infall/outflow rates than in similar galaxies.
This likely provokes a strong mixing of gas and a re-distribution of
metals.
