model with two options for the mass profile of the dark matter halo: an
unaltered and an adiabatically contracted Navarro, Frenk {\amp} White
(NFW) sphere. If we fix the local circular velocity, the latter profile
yields a significantly higher mass than the uncontracted halo, but if we
instead use the statistics for halo concentration parameters in large
cosmological simulations as a constraint, we find very similar masses
for both models. Our best estimate for M$_{340}$, the mass
interiorto R$_{340}$ (dark matter and baryons), is
1.3$^{+0.4}$$_{-0.3}$ {\times} 10$^{12}$
M$_{&sun;}$ (corresponds to M$_{200}$ =
1.6$^{+0.5}$$_{-0.4}$ {\times} 10$^{12}$
M$_{&sun;}$). This estimate is in good agreement with recently
published, independent mass estimates based on the kinematics of more
distant halo stars and the satellite galaxy Leo I.
