  Volume                   = {24},

  Abstract                 = {{In this article I briefly review recent abundance measurements in
intermediate- and high-velocity clouds (IVCs and HVCs, respectively) in
the halo of the Milky Way. FUSE and STIS absorption line data indicate
that these clouds span a metallicity range between \~{} 0.1-1.0 solar,
suggesting that they cannot have a single origin. Most likely, the
infall of gas from the intergalactic medium and from satellite galaxies
is responsible for the population of low-metallicity HVCs like Complex
C, while the more metal-rich clouds (in particular the IVCs) represent
Galactic material as part of a galactic fountain. The detailed analysis
