Leiden-Argentina-Bonn (LAB) survey. Metal absorption towards
RXJ0439.8-6809 is unambiguously detected in three different velocity
components near v\_LSR=0,+60, and +150 km/s. The presence of absorption
proves that all three gas components are situated in front of the star,
thus being located in the disk and inner halo of the Milky Way. For the
high-velocity cloud (HVC) at v\_LSR=+150 km/s we derive an oxygen
abundance of [O/H]=-0.63 (\~{}0.2 solar) from the neighbouring Sk-69 59
sightline, in accordance with previous abundance measurements for this
HVC. From the observed kinematics we infer that the HVC hardly
participates in the Galactic rotation. Our study shows that the HVC
