dust within one kiloparsec in the outer Galaxy, including many local
molecular clouds (Orion, Taurus, Perseus, California, and Cepheus), has
a significantly lower R(V) than more distant dust in the Milky Way.
These results provide new input to models of dust evolution and
processing, and complicate the application of locally derived extinction
curves to more distant regions of the Milky Way and to other galaxies.
