  Month                    = jul,
  Pages                    = {4050-4069},
  Volume                   = {450},

  Abstract                 = {{While it is incontrovertible that the inner Galaxy contains a bar, its
structure near the Galactic plane has remained uncertain, where
extinction from intervening dust is greatest. We investigate here the
Galactic bar outside the bulge, the long bar, using red clump giant
(RCG) stars from United Kingdom Infrared Deep Sky Survey, Two Micron All
Sky Survey, Vista Variables in the Via Lactea and Galactic Legacy
Infrared Midplane Survey Extraordinaire. We match and combine these
surveys to investigate a wide area in latitude and longitude, |b| {\le}
9{\deg} and |l| {\le} 40{\deg}. We find (i) the bar extends to l {\tilde}
25{\deg} at |b| {\tilde} 5{\deg} from the Galactic plane, and to l {\tilde}
30{\deg} at lower latitudes; (ii) the long bar has an angle to the
line-of-sight in the range (28{\deg}-33{\deg}), consistent with studies of
the bulge at |l| $\lt$ 10{\deg}; (iii) the scale height of RCG stars
smoothly transitions from the bulge to the thinner long bar; (iv) there
is evidence for two scale heights in the long bar; we find a {\tilde}180
pc thin bar component reminiscent of the old thin disc near the Sun, and
a {\tilde}45 pc superthin bar components which exist predominantly
towards the bar end; (v) constructing parametric models for the red
clump magnitude distributions, we find a bar half-length of 5.0 {\plusmn}
0.2 kpc for the two-component bar, and 4.6 {\plusmn} 0.3 kpc for the thin
bar component alone. We conclude that the Milky Way contains a central
box/peanut bulge which is the vertical extension of a longer, flatter
bar, similar as seen in both external galaxies and N-body models.
